{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_geordi_ver01/data/sn87055779/00517016925/1927071601/0492.xml":{"full_text":"l\" RAILROAD ONIONS\nSEE 8-HOOR THREAT\nI IN \u201cFLEXIBLE DAY\u201d\nBrotherhood Takes Up Chal\nlenge of Employers to In\ncrease Hours in Rush.\n\u25a0_\nBy FREDERIC WILLIAM WILE\nWASHINGTON, D. C. (EFS.)\u2014\nOfficial spokesmen of the powerful\nrailroad brotherhoods scent danger\nto the 8-hour day. They charge the\nAssociation of Railway Executives\nwith plotting the repeal 6f the Adam\nson law, whereby a 48-hour week\ncame into existence by act of Con\ngress during the war. The Brother\nhoods declare that the report of the\nrailway executives' special commit\ntee, submitted at the end of June, Is\nopen to no other construction. The\nreport is the result of three years\u2019\nstudy by a committee appointed in\n1824 at the suggestion of the Inter\nstate Commerce Commission. Its pur\npose was to evolv* ways and means\nof \u201cstabilizing employment.\u201d Daniel\nWillard, president of the Baltimore\nOhio, was chairman of the com\nmittee, which frankly advocates \"elas\nticity\" in the schedule of working\nhours, as a means af avoiding dis\nmissal of rail employes during slack\nseasons.\nThe portion of the railway execu\ntives\u2019 report, which has aroused the\nire and anxiety of the Brotherhoods,\nreads:\n\u201cInformation which has come to\nthis committee during its study of the\nproblem suggests the desirability of\na more flexible day than exists in\nmany places at the present time as\nan element to be considered \u2018in the\nstabilization of labor.\nAsk for \u201cElasticity\"\n\u201cWhile there seems to be a gen\neral tendency at the present time to\nrecognize the eight-hour day in most\nlines of employment, there is much\nto be said in favor of a certain elas\nticity in the number of horns to be\nworked.\n\u201cIf the day could be increased from\neight to nine, and even ten hours,\nin times of business activity, such a\npolicy would enable the carriers to\nemploy a more uniform force\nthroughout the year and avoid the\nnecessity of laying ofT or furloughing\nlarge numbers of men in times of\nbusiness recession.\u201d\nLabor, militant organ of the Rail\nroad Brotherhoods at Washington,\nannounces that the men\u2019s organiza\ntions will promptly and determinedly\ntake up the challenge which, it is\ncontended, the executives have now\nthrown down. \u201cIt can be said at\nence,\u201d the current issue of Labor\nsays, \u201cthat the rail labor organiza\ntions will fight this reactionary pro\nposal with every ounce of power they\npossess. Though the fact is care\nfully concealed from the average\nreader who does not know railroad\nworking conditions and agreements,\nthis proposal of a \u2018flexible working\nday\u2019 is a wage reduction scheme.\nRailroad workers cannot conceal\ntheir surprise that \u2018Dan\u2019 Willard and\n\u2018Pat\u2019 Crowley should have set their\nnames to such a report.\u201d\nClaim Reduction\nThe executives\u2019 committee which\nframed what Labor pillories as an\n\u201castounding program,\u201d consists of\nDaniel Willard (chairman:) L. W.\nBaldwin, of the Missouri Pacific; H.\nE. Byram, co-receiver of the St. Paul;\nW. H. Cole, of the Louisville Nash\nville; P. E. Crowley, of the New\nYork Central; C. R. Gray, of the\nUnion Pacific; L. F. Loree, of the\nDelaware Hudson; E. J. Pearson,\nof the New York, New Haven\nHartford; and Samuel Rea, former\npresident of the Pennsylvania.\nRailroad workers argue that their\nhours are \u201cflexible\u201d now. They say\nthat any employe can be kept on\nthe Job beyond the eight-hour period,\nif emergency requires, and frequently\nis. But if he works more, than eight\nhours, he gets excess pay. What the\nBrotherhoods are pointing out is that\nif the day is made \u201cflexible,\u201d as the\nexecutives suggest, excess pay for\nextra hours would be abolished.\nThis, the workers claim, is equiva\nlent to reducing wages.\nRoads Issue Denial\nPresident Willard denies there is\nany intention to impose extra hours\non the men. He says:\n\u201cThe proposal was made for labor\nto consider, as well as the railroads.\nThe plan would be for the men to\nwork an extra hour or two each day\nin rush periods only, instead of forc\ning the railroads to employ extra\nmen, who have to be discharged at\nthe end of the seasons of increased\nactivity.\n\u201cAdoption of the arrangement\nwould mean extra money for the\nmen during the periods of Increased\nactivity. When business returned to\nnormalcy, the men would only work\neight hours a day.\u201d\nTo all of which Labor, the Brother\nhoods\u2019 newspaper, retorts: \u201cIf the\ncamel of longer hours once gets his\nnose into the tent, he never will rest\ntill he takes full possession.\nFatty\u2019s Come-back\nBoscoe (Tatty\u201d) Arbuckle, whose\ntereen popularity ended with the no\ntorious Virginia Rapp case five yean\nigo, as he will shortly appear on the\nBroadway legitimate stage starring in\ni arrival of \u201cBaby Mine.\u201d This pio\nm was taken at a rehearsal.\nYburMarri\nLefsTakltOver!\nEM IffbxTJtxw\nTHIS HUSBAND SAYS: Zowie, but I hate the time of year\nwhen we live in an atmosphere of house cleaning and moth balls.\nThe house cleaning, of course, starts in the early spring and lasts\nover until, with the month of June or July, comes the putting\naway of winter duds. Gad, how\nI hate the smell of moth balls!\nMy wife, knowing my dislike\nfor same, has tried every other\nkind of moth destroyer. But\nthey all smell more or less alike.\nFrom early June on the house\nis unspeakable and I welcome\nthe closing of school for the chil\ndren and getting away to the\ncountry. Sometimes I wish my\nwife were less fussy. She says 1\nwould sing another song if she\nPatting away the winter duds i<\ndid let things go and every fall\nI were compelled to buy new drapes and all the heavy woolen\ntogs the children require for winter sports. Couldn\u2019t she put them\nin moth-proof bags that don\u2019t smell?\n9/i j\n\\H? HOW I HXT* TW SMEU\nr WOftfEN A CLum WOMO\ntATANMEKV IMAj\nTHIS WIFE SAYS: I read the \u201cWife\u2019s\u201d paragraph about marry\ning late in life and I heartily disagree with her views. Why de\nfer one\u2019s happiness? My experience has been so the opposite of\nhers that I must tell of same. When 18 I married a man of 20\nAt that time he was employed in an insurance company at a\nmedium salary. We did not expect easy times nor did we have\nthem. But I would not exchange those years of hard work and\nmutual fun for anything in life. They did more to hold us to\ngether than all the wealth in the world. We are now living a\nlife of comparative luxury but how we enjoy recalling the old\ndays. And I\u2019ll tell you a secret. Every year on our anniversary\nwe go back to the little brown cottage where we started out to\ngether. No servants, no children; just John and I. And for a\nweek we keep house there together. Suppose we had waited for\nJohn to start on die road to fortune. Think of all we should\nhave missed! And who knows? Perhaps John would not have\nwanted me then.\nTell The Readers Of This Newspaper Of Some\nIncident That Has Made YOUR Marriage Happy\nAll contributions treated confidentially\u2014no names used\nCopyright, 192V by The Georg* Mattbew Adams Servtca\n400 Girls\u2019 DRESSES\nReduced for Quick Clearance\nThe July Clearance brings 400 of our most desir-\ngirls\u2019 dresses down to less than cost. Printed\nand plain colored voiles with hand hemstitching y\nand embroidery. Pretty lace trimmings on most\nstyles. Thrifty mothers will buy several at this\nsacrifice price Saturday.\nLLOYD\u2019S\u2014FmST FLOOR\nHats Sacrificed\n500 Hats Formerly\nPriced to $7.50\n\n2\nThis Is a record low price for\nhats in our second floor mil*\nlinery salon. It should at\ntract hundreds here bright\nand early Saturday. Big as\nsortment of hats in scores\nand scores of styles. All\nshapes, colors and materials.\nLarge and small hats. 